Refusing to acknowledge these numbers only deepens public mistrust and guarantees further social fracture.

If your CEO is literally riding in the passenger seat while the car drives itself around a major U.S. city, with no safety monitor in the vehicle, that‚Äôs about as bullish of a signal you can send to the market that autonomy is here and Tesla has solved it.

This is Elon Musk, in Austin, letting Tesla‚Äôs AI do 100% of the work, confident enough in the technology to remove the last human supervision inside the vehicle.

What honesty makes this moment special to me is how long it‚Äôs been coming.

Tesla first talked about full autonomy back in 2016, when FSD was introduced as a long-term software promise. Since then, we‚Äôve had
‚Ä¢ years of real world data collection
‚Ä¢ multiple hardware generations
‚Ä¢ vision only going against industry consensus of LiDAR
‚Ä¢ endless doubt and skepticism, delays, and ‚Äúit‚Äôll never work‚Äù headlines

This is nearly a decade of hard work and intelligent iterations to reach this moment.

When the person with the most to lose is willing to trust the system with his own life, this debate now ends overnight. We‚Äôve been waiting for this day for almost 10 years‚Ä¶ 

Elon may not always be on time, may be very optimistic at times, but he and his team always delivers. 

Damn, it feels good to be a retail Tesla investor.

result.text:
Here is one surprisingly elegant equivalent reformulation of the Riemann Hypothesis: Let B be the pointwise maximal function on [0,1] satisfying B(0) = B(1) = 0 and 2B((x+y)/2) ‚â§ B(x) + B(y) + |x - y| for all x and y in [0,1]. Extend it periodically to all the real line.

As Grok correctly notes, this is Takagi function (or blancmange curve), with a fractal-like graph. It is continuous, nowhere differentiable, and less well-known than the Weierstrass function.
 
This function also emerged recently (and independently) in a joint work https://t.co/pgJw9MaEA1  with my student, Natanael Alpay, as a sharp lower bound for the L^1 norm of the square function applied to indicator functions of sets. I was unaware at the time that it is known as the Takagi function or of its connection to the Riemann Hypothesis. Large language models will undoubtedly accelerate scientific discoveries by forging connections across diverse fields of science.

result.text:
People assume that once they've set up a digital asset LLC, they've handled the legal side of their crypto holdings. The LLC is doing its job. It's protecting you from liability, maybe giving you some tax flexibility, keeping your personal assets separate from your crypto activities. That's real value.

But here's what an LLC doesn't do: it doesn't solve the problem of what happens when you die.

Your LLC is a business entity. You own it. When you die, your ownership interest in that LLC becomes part of your estate. And unless you've done something specific to prevent it, that ownership interest goes through probate. The exact same probate process that makes crypto inheritance such a nightmare for people holding assets in their personal name.

Probate is public. Court filings become records anyone can search. So now your LLC ownership, which you created partly for privacy, gets documented in a courthouse somewhere. The irony is brutal.
Probate is slow. Six months minimum, often 12 to 18 months if there are any complications. During that time, your family might not be able to access the LLC's assets. They can't make decisions about selling, can't manage DeFi positions that need attention, can't respond to market conditions. They just wait while lawyers bill hours.

Probate is expensive. Fees typically run 3 to 7 percent of the estate value. On a million dollar crypto portfolio, that's thirty to seventy thousand dollars gone before your family sees anything.
A living trust fixes all of this.

When you create a living trust, you're creating a legal container that holds assets. The trust owns things. You control the trust completely while you're alive. You're the trustee, you make all the decisions, nothing changes day to day. But when you die, the trust doesn't die with you. It just continues existing, and your successor trustee takes over.

No probate. No court involvement. No public records. No waiting.
The way this works with your LLC is straightforward. You transfer your ownership interest in the LLC to your living trust. The trust becomes the member of the LLC instead of you personally. You still control everything because you control the trust. But now when you die, the LLC membership interest passes according to the trust instructions, not through probate court.

This is where the combination gets powerful.

Your LLC handles liability protection and operational structure. It's the entity that holds wallets, interacts with exchanges, maybe runs staking operations or other activities. The LLC operating agreement defines how the business works.

Your living trust handles succession and privacy. It's the entity that owns the LLC and determines what happens to that ownership when you're gone. The trust document includes detailed instructions for your successor trustee about how to access everything, what to do with different assets, who gets what and when.

One structure without the other leaves gaps.
LLC without trust: Your family faces probate, delays, public records, and all the costs that come with them. Your crypto might sit inaccessible for over a year while courts sort things out.

Trust without LLC: You're missing liability protection and the operational benefits an LLC provides. If something goes wrong with a DeFi protocol or an exchange hack, your personal assets could be exposed.

Both together: You get liability protection, operational structure, privacy, probate avoidance, and clear succession planning. Your successor trustee can step in immediately, access the LLC, and manage or distribute assets according to your wishes.

There's another piece people don't think about until it's too late. What happens if you become incapacitated before you die? Car accident, stroke, sudden illness. You're alive but you can't manage your crypto.

An LLC by itself doesn't help here. Someone would need to go to court to get authority over your affairs, which takes time and money and creates public records.

A living trust with proper incapacity provisions lets your successor trustee step in and manage things without any court involvement. The trust document can specify exactly when and how this happens. Two family members plus a doctor provide written statements that you can't manage your affairs, and the successor trustee takes over. Clean, private, immediate.

For crypto investors specifically, this matters more than it does for people with traditional assets. Banks have procedures. Brokerages have customer service. If your family can prove who they are and that you're dead or incapacitated, institutions will eventually cooperate.

Crypto doesn't work that way. There's no customer service number for your hardware wallet. If your family doesn't have the information and authority to access your holdings, those holdings might as well not exist. 

The combination of an LLC and a living trust creates both the operational structure and the succession framework that actually works for how crypto ownership functions.

The LLC is your shield while you're alive. The trust is your bridge to whoever comes next.

For centuries, the diagnosis was clear: power corrupts, institutions betray, and liberty yields to control by gradual encroachment.

The thinkers saw it. Spinoza. Paine. Jefferson. Spooner. Bastiat. Hayek. Mises. Brandeis. They came from different centuries, spoke different languages, and agreed on almost nothing‚Äîexcept this: concentrated power is the enemy of human freedom, and no constitution, no election, no reform has ever kept it restrained for long.

They could diagnose. They could not cure.

Now the cure exists. Not in philosophy but in architecture. Not in argument but in code. Not in trust but in proof.

This is what I believe. This is how I will act.

ùóú. ùóüùó∂ùóØùó≤ùóøùòÅùòÜ ùóóùóºùó≤ùòÄ ùó°ùóºùòÅ ùóîùòÄùó∏

Liberty does not beg. It does not petition. It does not wait for approval from those who have no authority to grant it.

Anything that must be granted is not a right. It is a license. And licenses can be revoked.

This is the lie at the center of modern governance: that freedom flows downward from institutions that exist only because individuals surrendered nothing they did not already possess.

Paine understood: "Man did not enter into society to become worse than he was before, nor to have fewer rights than he had before, but to have those rights better secured."

Jefferson made it the founding premise: rights are not gifts from government but endowments from nature. Governments are instituted to secure them‚Äîand when governments destroy them, they forfeit their legitimacy.

I start from the presumption of liberty.

The burden is on power to justify itself‚Äînot on me to justify being left alone.

ùóúùóú. ùó£ùóºùòÑùó≤ùóø ùóúùòÄ ùòÅùóµùó≤ ùóóùó∂ùòÄùó≤ùóÆùòÄùó≤

The default condition of the individual is freedom.

The default condition of power is abuse.

This is not cynicism. It is observation.

Every authority claims necessity. Every authority promises restraint. Every authority eventually breaks both promises.

Madison saw it: "There are more instances of the abridgment of the freedom of the people by gradual and silent encroachments of those in power than by violent and sudden usurpations."

Jefferson saw it: "The natural progress of things is for liberty to yield and government to gain ground."

Bastiat watched law become plunder: "When plunder becomes a way of life for a group of men in a society, over the course of time they create for themselves a legal system that authorizes it and a moral code that glorifies it."

Every centralized institution follows the same arc: Protection ‚Üí Management ‚Üí Control ‚Üí Extraction.

This is not a failure of implementation. It is the natural life cycle of concentrated power. Reform does not stop it. Oversight does not stop it. Elections do not stop it. Good intentions do not stop it.

The pattern repeats because the incentives are structural. The problem is not bad actors. The problem is architecture that requires trusting actors at all.

Good people do not redeem bad systems. They get consumed by them.

I do not trust power. I watch it. I constrain it. When possible, I route around it entirely.

ùóúùóúùóú. ùóñùóºùóªùòÄùó≤ùóªùòÅ ùó™ùó∂ùòÅùóµùóºùòÇùòÅ ùóòùòÖùó∂ùòÅ ùóúùòÄ ùóñùóºùó≤ùóøùó∞ùó∂ùóºùóª

I did not sign this contract.

My parents could not sign it for me.

Silence is not consent. Residence is not consent. Birth is not consent. Benefit is not consent.

Spooner asked the question polite theorists avoid: "The Constitution has no inherent authority or obligation. It has no authority or obligation at all, unless as a contract between man and man."

Who signed? Not me. Not you. Not anyone alive.

Systems that deny exit rule by force, not legitimacy. Compliance extracted by punishment is not agreement‚Äîit is captivity with paperwork.

If you cannot leave, you are not a participant. You are a subject.

I recognize no obligation I did not assume. I respect no authority that forbids its own rejection.

ùóúùó©. ùóßùóµùóºùòÇùó¥ùóµùòÅ ùóúùòÄ ùòÅùóµùó≤ ùóôùó∂ùóªùóÆùóπ ùó•ùó≤ùó≥ùòÇùó¥ùó≤

Every authoritarian project begins the same way: not with guns, but with words you are no longer permitted to say. Ideas you are no longer permitted to hold. Questions you are no longer permitted to ask.

Spinoza understood that the state may regulate conduct‚Äîwithin limits‚Äîbut may never regulate thought: "The purpose of the state is not to dominate or control people by fear... The true purpose of the state is freedom."

Jefferson swore "upon the altar of God eternal hostility against every form of tyranny over the mind of man."

Control thought, and you control behavior.

Control belief, and force becomes unnecessary.

A state that polices ideas has confessed it cannot rule by legitimacy‚Äîonly by fear. It has forfeited its claim to anything but resistance.

There is no such thing as dangerous speech. There is only speech dangerous to power.

I defend the thought I hate, because the power to suppress it will never stay limited to ideas I oppose.

ùó©. ùó£ùóøùó∂ùòÉùóÆùó∞ùòÜ ùóúùòÄ ùòÅùóµùó≤ ùóôùóºùòÇùóªùó±ùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª

Brandeis called it "the right to be let alone‚Äîthe most comprehensive of rights and the right most valued by civilized men."

He was not overstating.

Without privacy, there is no freedom of thought‚Äîyou cannot think freely while watched.

Without freedom of thought, there is no genuine consent.

Without genuine consent, there is no legitimate law.

Surveillance is not security. It is the infrastructure of domination.

A watched population cannot think freely. A population that cannot think freely cannot meaningfully resist. That is not a side effect. That is the purpose.

Total visibility is total control‚Äîwhether imposed by governments or corporations. The ledger is the leash. The database is the chain.

I guard my privacy not because I have secrets, but because I refuse to be managed.

ùó©ùóú. ùóßùóµùó≤ ùóûùóªùóºùòÑùóπùó≤ùó±ùó¥ùó≤ ùóßùóµùóÆùòÅ ùóñùóÆùóªùóªùóºùòÅ ùóïùó≤ ùóñùóºùó∫ùó∫ùóÆùóªùó±ùó≤ùó±

Hayek identified the fatal conceit: the belief that any central authority can possess the knowledge required to direct society.

It cannot.

Knowledge is dispersed among millions of individuals, embedded in local circumstances, preferences, and relationships no planner can access. Prices transmit this knowledge. Markets coordinate it. Central planning destroys it.

Mises proved it formally: without market prices, rational economic calculation is impossible. Socialism does not fail because of bad implementation. It fails because it destroys the information system that makes complex coordination possible.

And every intervention creates the justification for the next. Each distortion creates problems. Each problem is blamed on insufficient control. The ratchet turns one direction.

Hayek saw where it ends: the road to serfdom. Central economic planning requires central control of life. You cannot direct production without directing producers. You cannot allocate resources without allocating people.

Economic liberty and political liberty are not separate goods. They are the same good, viewed from different angles.

I oppose the first intervention‚Äînot because I cannot imagine it working, but because I can see where the road leads.

ùó©ùóúùóú. ùó£ùó≤ùóøùó∫ùó∂ùòÄùòÄùó∂ùóºùóª ùóúùòÄ ùòÅùóµùó≤ ùó†ùó≤ùó∞ùóµùóÆùóªùó∂ùòÄùó∫

Money that requires approval. Speech that requires platforms. Identity that requires registration. Travel that requires documentation. Participation that requires compliance.

Every permission is a chokepoint. Every chokepoint will be used. The question is not whether, but when‚Äîand against whom.

Power does not need to ban what it can simply deny access to. Censorship is crude. Exclusion from infrastructure is elegant‚Äîand deniable.

Jefferson saw it in banks. Hayek saw it in central planning. Mises saw it in monetary manipulation. The mechanism changes. The logic remains: control the infrastructure, control the people.

I design my life to minimize dependency on systems that require permission.

Every permission I eliminate is a lever of control I have removed from hands that will eventually seek to use it.

ùó©ùóúùóúùóú. ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùóõùóÆùòÉùó≤ ùóôùó≤ùóπùòÅ ùòÅùóµùó≤ ùóñùóÆùó¥ùó≤

You have watched your words before posting‚Äînot because they were wrong, but because they were inconvenient.

You have seen your account suspended without explanation, your reach throttled without acknowledgment, your content removed without appeal.

You have watched money move slowly when it should move instantly‚Äîand known that the delay was not technical but political. Someone was watching. Someone was deciding.

You have filled out forms that demanded information no one should require. You have submitted to searches that presumed your guilt. You have complied with rules that existed only to remind you who holds power.

You have watched the same institutions that failed you demand more trust, more data, more control‚Äîalways for your protection, never with your consent.

You knew something was wrong.

You were right.

The feeling in your chest when you self-censored‚Äîthat was not paranoia. That was the system working as designed.

This manifesto is for everyone who felt that and refused to accept it as normal.

ùóúùó´. ùóßùóµùó≤ ùóñùòÇùóøùó≤

For three hundred years, we knew the disease but had no cure.

We could see that power corrupts. We could see that institutions betray. We could see that every system requiring trust would eventually exploit it.

But we had no alternative. To coordinate at scale, we needed institutions. To have institutions, we needed administrators. To have administrators, we needed trust.

And trust, inevitably, was betrayed.

Then Satoshi asked a different question:

What if we didn't need trust at all?

"What is needed is an electronic payment system based on cryptographic proof instead of trust."

One sentence. Everything changed.

Cryptography does what constitutions promised and failed to deliver: Rules that enforce themselves. Systems without administrators. Coordination without permission. Exit without reprisal. Money without masters.

Hayek dreamed of denationalizing money. He could not see how.

Mises proved sound money was the foundation of freedom. He could not build it.

Jefferson hoped for a republic beyond the reach of tyrants. He could not architect it.

Now we can.

This is not theory. It is running code. Where trust once made tyranny inevitable, proof now makes it optional.

I do not petition power to reform. I build systems that do not require its cooperation.

ùó´. ùóóùó≤ùó∞ùó≤ùóªùòÅùóøùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª ùóúùòÄ ùó°ùóºùóª-ùó°ùó≤ùó¥ùóºùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóØùóπùó≤

This is not about efficiency. It is not about innovation. It is not about disruption.

It is about the possibility of liberty in a world of pervasive control.

Hayek's deepest insight was not economic but epistemological: the most complex and beneficial social arrangements are not designed. They emerge. Language was not designed. Law‚Äîreal law, not legislation‚Äîevolved from custom and practice. Markets coordinate billions of decisions no committee could comprehend, let alone direct.

Spontaneous order arises from freedom. Designed order requires coercion.

Liberty cannot coexist with systems that have single points of failure‚Äîbecause single points of failure are single points of capture.

If a system has a switch, someone will flip it.

If it has an administrator, someone will capture it.

If it has no exit, it will become a cage.

The only durable protection is architecture that requires no protection‚Äîsystems where the rules are enforced by mathematics, not men; where no single party can alter the terms; where participation requires no gatekeeper's blessing.

Decentralization is not my preference. It is my requirement.

ùó´ùóú. ùóßùóµùó≤ ùó¶ùòÅùóÆùóªùó±ùóÆùóøùó±

I judge every system‚Äîtechnical, legal, political, economic‚Äîby the same criteria:

Autonomy: Does it require permission, or does it respect self-determination?

Exit: Does it enable departure, or does it punish it?

Privacy: Does it protect opacity for the individual, or does it demand transparency from the powerless while granting secrecy to the powerful?

Dispersion: Does it distribute power, or does it concentrate it?

Consent: Does it rest on genuine agreement, or does it presume compliance?

Systems that fail these tests are not neutral. They are hostile to liberty‚Äîwhatever their stated intentions, whatever their official justifications.

I do not use what I do not trust. I do not depend on what I cannot exit. I do not accept what I did not choose.

ùó´ùóúùóú. ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùóú ùó™ùó∂ùóπùóπ ùó°ùóºùòÅ ùóóùóº

I will not beg for rights I already possess.

I will not ask permission from those who have no authority to grant it.

I will not comply with demands that rest on nothing but the threat of force.

I will not pretend that procedure legitimizes plunder, that votes sanctify theft, or that laws passed by strangers bind my conscience.

I will not use systems designed to surveil me when alternatives exist.

I will not store value in currencies designed to be debased.

I will not trust platforms that can silence me with a policy change.

I will not depend on institutions that have demonstrated, repeatedly, that they will betray every trust placed in them.

I will not wait.

ùó´ùóúùóúùóú. ùóßùóµùó≤ ùóñùóºùó∫ùó∫ùó∂ùòÅùó∫ùó≤ùóªùòÅ

I commit to building and supporting systems that recognize rights rather than grant them, require actual consent and permit exit, protect privacy by design not by promise, disperse power rather than concentrate it, enforce rules through protocol rather than discretion, operate permissionlessly requiring no approval to access, enable spontaneous coordination without central direction, and preserve sound money beyond the reach of manipulation.

I commit to minimizing my dependence on systems that fail these standards‚Äînot because withdrawal is comfortable, but because dependency is dangerous.

I commit to helping others do the same.

ùó´ùóúùó©. ùóßùóµùó≤ ùóîùóªùòÄùòÑùó≤ùóø

Spinoza saw that freedom of thought is the foundation.

Paine saw that rights precede government.

Jefferson swore eternal hostility to tyranny over the mind.

Spooner asked who actually consented.

Bastiat identified legal plunder.

Smith warned of conspiracy against the public.

Mises proved central planning cannot calculate.

Hayek showed knowledge cannot be centralized.

Brandeis drew the line at the right to be let alone.

Satoshi asked: What if we didn't need permission?

They asked the questions.

Now the answers are running.

Not in theory. In code.

Not in hope. In mathematics.

Not waiting for permission. Operating without it.

The old systems will fight. They will call this dangerous.

They are right. It is dangerous‚Äîto them.

To everyone else, it is the first real answer in three hundred years.

I am not asking for freedom.

I am building it.

And I am not building alone.

Trust is the vulnerability. Capture is the method. Betrayal is the destination.

Protocol is the exit.

‚Äî Wernick
